76561198052436469,Recommended,260730,33596309,Posted: 16 July,all,Hekateras,"I played the game a lot as a kid (in German at the time, though it was an EXCELLENT localisation) and it's been a pleasure to rediscover it now and discover that it's just as good as I remember.Very brief description: you control up to six different characters at a time (depending on plot progression and mission), each with unique abilities, and have to make use of them to complete the map with various objectives, usually eliminating or otherwise taking out most enemies in the process.The plot is fairly interesting, but not the focus. Gameplay is the main pleasure. The controls are extremely intuitive and the design is full of little details that you sometimes have to discover by yourself regarding how best to eliminate the enemies. Often using elaborate lure and distraction tactics. There is usually an easier and more elegant way (involving a specific ability) to get past big obstacles in the game (for example, a gang of bandits showing up to besiege the tower you're trying to kidnap their leader from), but raw persistence and shoot-outs will also eventually solve the problem. AI is pretty good and includes a lot of potential complications for you - mooks tend to band together, send underlings to explore suspicious noises, call for help, etc. Sometimes, but not always, they'll be adept at spotting things out of the ordinary (such as a missing patrol partner or a horse wandering around by itself) and might even raise the alarm just because of that. Enemies tend to be just as good at shooting as the protagonists. Quicksaving and reloading often demonstrates that enemies sometimes take slightly different approaches even to identical situations, so there's a good degree of unpredicability. Quite often, difficult situations arise spontaneously, such as an enemy spotting you when you hadn't realised he was there, or your desperados being held at gunpoint when they were safe just a moment ago. It makes for fairly unpredictable, adrenaline-filled strategising, and these situations can be extremely thrilling. By occasonionally switching up the combination of characters available to you, the game also does a good job forcing you to adapt your tactics and come up with new things. Combat is fairly realistic - shooting lethality and accuracy decreases dramatically with distance, but guns are almost invariably instantly lethal at short range. Most of the characters have a firearm as the primary weapon, but each has a slightly different one - for example a revolver, a rifle, a small handgun, a shotgun, and a long-barrelled Colt that can be converted into a sort of sniper rifle. They all have different attributes in terms of reach, loudness of the shot, reload speed and magazine size, so are best suited for different situations. Care must be taken when shooting if the weapons begin to overheat. The same level of detail and variety applies to the environment, with some elements having different effects on how far sound carries, for example. In short, some very nice gameplay design, thoughtful and detailed without being overcomplicated or ceasing to be intuitive.Cons: I can't trully come up with negative points for this game except that maybe the story and characters might be a bit too simplistic for some tastes. (Personally, I think it works the same way often simple characterisation for adventure movies works.) In this and other ways, the game is a little bit dated, having come out in 2001. Though I think the graphics, even the 3D movies, actually withstood the test of time very well, it's obviously not on the level of modern games. In terms of characterisation, the overuse of Mexican stereotypes (and Chinese ones, to an extent) would rightfully be seen as too crude today. Though on the flip side, not every game made in 2001 had a multiracial cast that was also one third female, so that deserves some points. On the gameplay side, there were some moments when I felt that the quickest, simplest way through a level relied too much on weaknesses of AI (for example, running towards gunshot sounds into a pile of corpses where you'd hidden a snake in the shadows without a second thought). (Sam's rattlesnake was borderline gamebreaking at points for the body count it had, but it was balanced by how quickly enemies would kill it if they spotted it in advance, and by how few spots were actually suitable for it.)I recommend this game if you like Commandos-style gameplay coated in a layer of pleasantly familiar Wild West cliches. ;)"
,Recommended,260730,29139462,Posted: 9 January,all,Amdir,"Desperados is a fantastic tactical game that manages to build up the atmosphere of the Wild West as well as games like Red Dead Redemption. Back in the old days I first came across this game through the Demo Disc that came with Kellogg's cornflakes. The demo was fun, which made me buy the game afterwards and I can't recall how many hours I spent playing this game.It was one of my favourites when it was released, and still today I really love it. You can play the game in many different ways and solve the missions either by shooting your way out, or using stealth. The story and the characters are great, but most of all the map design is amazing.Sadly the game does not work too well on modern computers, but using DxWnd it has worked really well on my computer. If you want to play this game, be prepared to do some fiddling to get it to work. Even though it can be a bit messy, when you get it to work this is a great game for all Wild West lovers.A thread named ""Workaround Windows 7 / 8.1 / 10"" can be found in the game's forum, which will guide you through the process of making the game work.Score for the game: 9/10Score for the poor port: 2/10"
